Ch. 7 Interactions

A Solomon Kurz

2018-09-17

Load the rethinking package and the rugged data.

library(rethinking)

data(rugged)
d <- rugged
rm(rugged)

Now load the tidyverse and wrangle the data a bit.

library(tidyverse)

# make the log version of criterion
d <- 
  d %>%
  mutate(log_gdp = log(rgdppc_2000))

# extract countries with GDP data
dd <-
  d %>%
  filter(complete.cases(rgdppc_2000))

# split countries into Africa and not-Africa
d.A1 <-
  dd %>%
  filter(cont_africa == 1)

d.A0 <-
  dd %>%
  filter(cont_africa == 0)

b7.1

The likelihood for the univariable model with the d.A1 data is

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{log_gdp}_{\text{data = d.A1}_i} & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta \text{rugged}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(8, 100) \\ \beta & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

Before we plot, lets make our custom plotting function, make_scatter().

make_scatter <- function(data, mapping, ...){
  ggplot(data, mapping) +
  geom_abline(color = "white") +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/2, size = 1/2) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank()) +
  facet_wrap(~index, scales = "free_y", ncol = 4)
}
set.seed(7.1)
d.A1 %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, log_gdp, rugged), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha       = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 8, sd = 100),
         beta        = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         sigma       = runif(n = n(), 0, 10)) %>% 
  mutate(sim_log_gdp = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta * rugged, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = log_gdp, y = sim_log_gdp))

b7.2

The likelihood for the next univariable model, b7.2, is very much the same as the last. The only difference is this time we use the d.A0 data.

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{log_gdp}_{\text{data = d.A0}_i} & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta \text{rugged}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(8, 100) \\ \beta & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.2)
d.A0 %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, log_gdp, rugged), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha       = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 8, sd = 100),
         beta        = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         sigma       = runif(n = n(), 0, 10)) %>% 
  mutate(sim_log_gdp = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta * rugged, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = log_gdp, y = sim_log_gdp))

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{log_gdp}_{\text{data = dd}_i} & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta \text{rugged}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(8, 100) \\ \beta & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.3)
dd %>%

b7.4

With model b7.4 we finally switch the likelihood up a bit.

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{log_gdp}_{\text{data = dd}_i} & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta_1 \text{rugged}_i + \beta_2 \text{cont_africa}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(8, 100) \\ \beta_1 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \beta_2 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.4)
dd %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, log_gdp, rugged, cont_africa), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha       = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 8, sd = 100),
         beta_1      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         beta_2      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         sigma       = runif(n = n(), 0, 10)) %>% 
  mutate(sim_log_gdp = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta_1 * rugged + beta_2 * cont_africa, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = log_gdp, y = sim_log_gdp))

b7.5

The likelihood for b7.5 follows the form

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{log_gdp}_{\text{data = dd}_i} & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \gamma_i \text{rugged}_i + \beta_2 \text{cont_africa}_i \\ \gamma_i & = & \beta_1 + \beta_3 \text{cont_africa}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(8, 100) \\ \beta_1 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \beta_2 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \beta_3 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.5)
dd %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, log_gdp, rugged, cont_africa), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha       = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 8, sd = 100),
         beta_1      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         beta_2      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         beta_3      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         sigma       = runif(n = n(), 0, 10)) %>% 
  mutate(gamma       = beta_1 + beta_3 * cont_africa) %>% 
  mutate(sim_log_gdp = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + gamma * rugged + beta_2 * cont_africa, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = log_gdp, y = sim_log_gdp))

b7.5b

The likelihood for b7.5b follows the more-conventional form

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{log_gdp}_i & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta_1 \text{rugged}_i + \beta_2 \text{cont_africa}_i + \beta_3 \text{rugged}_i \times \text{cont_africa}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(8, 100) \\ \beta_1 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \beta_2 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \beta_3 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.5)
dd %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, log_gdp, rugged, cont_africa), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha       = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 8, sd = 100),
         beta_1      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         beta_2      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         beta_3      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 1),
         sigma       = runif(n = n(), 0, 10)) %>% 
  mutate(sim_log_gdp = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta_1 * rugged + beta_2 * cont_africa + beta_3 * rugged * cont_africa, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = log_gdp, y = sim_log_gdp))

b7.6

The next model requires the tulips data.

data(tulips)
d <- tulips
rm(tulips)

The likelihood for b7.6 follows the form

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{blooms}_i & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta_1 \text{water}_i + \beta_2 \text{shade}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \beta_1 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \beta_2 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 100) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.6)
d %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, blooms, water, shade), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         beta_1     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         beta_2     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         sigma      = runif(n = n(), 0, 100)) %>% 
  mutate(sim_blooms = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta_1 * water + beta_2 * shade, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = blooms, y = sim_blooms))

b7.7

The likelihood for model b7.7 added an interaction term.

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{blooms}_i & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta_1 \text{water}_i + \beta_2 \text{shade}_i + \beta_3 \text{water}_i \times \text{shade}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \beta_1 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \beta_2 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \beta_3 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{Uniform}(0, 100) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.7)
d %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, blooms, water, shade), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         beta_1     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         beta_2     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         beta_3     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         sigma      = runif(n = n(), 0, 100)) %>% 
  mutate(sim_blooms = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta_1 * water + beta_2 * shade + beta_3 * water * shade, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = blooms, y = sim_blooms))

b7.8

The next two likelihoods require us to center the predictors.

d <-
  d %>%
  mutate(shade_c = shade - mean(shade),
         water_c = water - mean(water))

Now the likelihood for b7.8 follows the form

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \text{blooms}_i & \sim & \text{Normal} (\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = & \alpha + \beta_1 \text{water_c}_i + \beta_2 \text{shade_c}_i \\ \alpha & \sim & \text{Normal}(130, 100) \\ \beta_1 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \beta_2 & \sim & \text{Normal}(0, 100) \\ \sigma & \sim & \text{HalfCauchy}(0, 10) \end{eqnarray} \]

set.seed(7.8)
d %>% 
  mutate(row = 1:n()) %>% 
  expand(nesting(row, blooms, water_c, shade_c), index = letters[1:4]) %>% 
  mutate(alpha      = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 130, sd = 100),
         beta_1     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         beta_2     = rnorm(n = n(), mean = 0, sd = 100),
         sigma      = rcauchy(n = n(), location = 0, scale = 10) %>% abs()) %>% 
  mutate(sim_blooms = rnorm(n = n(),
                             mean = alpha + beta_1 * water_c + beta_2 * shade_c, 
                             sd   = sigma)) %>% 
  
  make_scatter(aes(x = blooms, y = sim_blooms))
